US food, drug regulator to open offices in China: official The US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) will open its first overseas offices in China this year as part of efforts to regulate imported food to the United States, an official said on Thursday. The move reflected the increased globalization of the world's food and drug trade, notably from developing to developed nations, he said. "Opening these offices will mark a key milestone in the globalization of our efforts to enhance the safety of imported food and medical products," he said. Food quality concerns for imported goods are paramount for the FDA after recent high profile cases involving China. The first office will open by the end of 2008 in Beijing, with additional staff to be posted in Beijing, Shanghai and Guangzhou in 2009. Over the last month countries around the world have issued recalls and bans of Chinese-made dairy products after high levels of the chemical melamine were detected in exported goods. In total, 46,810 children were hospitalized after drinking milk tainted with melamine, which was added in place of water to increase sales volume. Figures from China's Ministry of Health said 5,824 children were still receiving hospital treatment for kidney diseases due to the tainted products, according to a report from state news agency "The globalization of the food supply and medical product manufacturing has demanded that we do things differently," said FDA Commissioner Andrew C. von Eschenbach. Last year, the US imported more than two trillion dollars worth of products from around 825,000 inmporters. HHS and FDA projections indicate the volume of imports will grow as the international trade continues to multiply. "Increasing our presence overseas will provide greater protections to American consumers at home and benefit our host countries as well," said Leavitt. "We won't have to send our experts to another country to work with foreign governments and regulated industry to improve our oversight -- we'll have staff living there and working on the ground 365 days a year."

Authorities were bracing for potentially more violence in Greece Tuesday as mourners prepared for the funeral of a teenager whose death in a police shooting sparked the worst riots the country has seen in decades. Fifteen-year-old Alexandros Grigoriadis died of a gunshot wound to the chest Saturday night in the often volatile downtown Athens district of Exarchia. Two police officers have been arrested and Within hours of the boy's death, riots erupted in cities across Greece, from Thessaloniki in the north to cities in Crete and the holiday island of Corfu. By early Tuesday, hundreds of stores, cars, banks and buildings in about a dozen cities had been torched, smashed or looted. Gangs of masked and hooded youths screaming "Cops! Pigs! Murderers!" fought pitched street battles with riot police firing volleys of tear gas. Black smoke mingled with clouds of tear gas above central Athens, which saw extensive damage. Broken glass littered the streets. Prime Minister Costas Karamanlis, whose increasingly unpopular conservative government has already faced a growing number of sometimes violent demonstrations against economic and education reforms, called for calm Monday. "All the dangerous and unacceptable events that occurred because of the emotions that followed the tragic incident cannot and will not be tolerated," he said in a live televised address. In an outpouring of rage, high school and university students joined self-styled anarchists in attacking police stations, smashing stores and burning buildings. Police said some rioters in central Syntagma Square. Protesters posed for photos in front In Athens, rioters torched the capital's massive Christmas tree of the blaze as others sang "Oh Christmas Tree." Police said rioting was abating in the early hours of Tuesday, although some clashes continued in the center of the capital. Dozens of masked youths were holed up in a university building. The widely televised scenes of destruction are likely to further undermine a government already rocked by financial scandals and clinging to a razor-thin majority of just one seat in the consistently in recent opinion polls for the first time in eight 300-member Parliament. But instead of taking it, he is rejecting the ... resignations of the responsible ministers, he is adopting the version of an isolated incident and barricading himself behind broken storefronts," after which Interior Minister Prokopis Pavlopoulos, whose weekend Karamanlis called a late-night emergency Cabinet meeting Monday, offer to resign was rejected, described the riots as "unacceptable." But he insisted police responded as well as they could. Although there is little public support for street violence, there is a deep well of tolerance for demonstrations in Greece, where the right to protest is held dear. Violence often breaks out between riot police and anarchists during demonstrations. Nepal's capital in a general strike Thursday protesting alleged Activists chanted slogans and halted traffic by burning tires in killings by former communist rebels who head the country's coalition government.  Strikers accuse members of the Young Communist League, the youth wing of Communist Party of Nepal (Maoist) which leads the coalition government, of killing two supporters of the Communist Party of Nepal (United Marxist-Leninist), the second largest communist party in the Himalayan nation. Although the two communist parties are partners in the government, there have been several clashes between their members over influence and control of voters and trade unions. The Young Communist League has denied involvement in the deaths. Its chief, Ganesh Pun, told reporters Thursday that it did not kill the two men and was also investigating the incident. Protest over killings shuts down Nepal ' s capital KATMANDU, Nepal 2008-11-20 06:08:14 UTC

Former England coach Duncan Fletcher has been approached to coach  the Highveld Lions franchise in South Africa, according to a Johannesburg newspaper. Fletcher, 59, has been living in Cape Town and has not been involved in coaching since leaving the England job in April 2007. Alan Kourie, chief executive of the Johannesburg-based Lions franchise, would not comment but it is understood he had discussions with Fletcher in Cape Town last week. The Lions have had a poor season and are set to finish last in the six-team SuperSport Series first-class competition. Fletcher, a former Zimbabwe captain, started his first-class coaching career with Western Province in the 1993/94 season after moving to South Africa and attracting attention as a part-time coach of the University of Cape Town team. during Fletcher's five-season stint and Fletcher played a Western Province won two South African first-class championships significant role in the development of Gary Kirsten, Herschelle Gibbs and Jacques Kallis, who all went on to become successful international batsmen. Western Province gave Fletcher leave of absence to coach Glamorgan in 1997 and 1998 and Glamorgan won the English county championship in 1997. The Sunday Times in Johannesburg reported that the Lions are keen to appoint Fletcher as soon as possible, with two limited overs competitions still to be played in the remaining three months of the season, but that there were significant obstacles including Fletcher's tax situations and his wife's health.

Canadian Pacific Railway reaches tentative contract with striking maintenance workers The Teamsters union announced Wednesday a tentative contract deal with Canadian Pacific Railway Ltd. and says a strike by 3,200 maintenance workers in Canada will end soon. The freight carrier is Canada's second biggest railway, with 2006 revenues of nearly 4.6 billion Canadian dollars ($4.3 billion; euro3.18 billion) a profit of nearly 800 million Canadian dollars ($755 million (euro558.72 million) and more than 15,300 employees While the Calgary-based railway had been strike-free for four years until the latest walkout, its larger rival Canadian National Railway Company suffered a two-week long strike by locomotive drivers and maintenance workers in February that impacted shippers from automotive parts manufacturers in Ontario Maintenance employees, who repair tracks and other railway infrastructure, have been without a contract since December 2006. Shippers worried about the impact of a prolonged strike but railway officials said service has not been disrupted. CP Rail has replaced about 1,200 striking workers with trained management for the duration of the strike.

Report: Chinese automaker FAW Group eyeing stake in Chrysler Chinese automaker FAW Group Corp. refused comment Tuesday on a report it is considering bidding for a stake in DaimlerChrysler AG's ailing Chrysler Group. The Shanghai-based Oriental Morning Post said FAW had sent representatives to the United States to negotiate a deal for a unspecified stake in Chrysler, citing an unnamed person familiar Staff at the FAW Group headquarters' publicity office refused comment on the report. DaimlerChrysler's public relations department in Beijing also would not comment. FAW, based in the northeastern city of Changchun, is one of China's biggest automobile makers and a local partner of Toyota Motor Corp. and Volkswagen AG.

Sex crime keeps Canadian soldier out of Afghanistan A Canadian soldier keen to deploy to Afghanistan will instead likely be discharged from the military after being convicted of sexual assault, officials said Thursday. Private Pier-Olivier Boulet, 22, was convicted in February of raping his friend's sister in 2004. The well-regarded soldier had sought an absolute discharge that would have allowed him to fulfill his dream of serving in Afghanistan, claiming the sex was consensual. But a judge on Thursday refused, sentencing him instead to 15 months of house arrest.

The Kermadec islands are uninhabited apart from Raoul, where New  Zealand's Department of Conservation maintains a field station. Strong quake jolts remote islands off New Zealand A 6.0 magnitude earthquake struck the remote Kermadec islands north of New Zealand on Tuesday, the US Geological Survey reported. The epicentre of the quake, recorded at 1:36pm (2336 GMT Monday), was 131 kilometres (81 miles) from Raoul Island and at a depth of 35 kilometres. Earthquakes and volcanic activity are common in the area, which is part of the "Ring of Fire" where the Pacific plate of the earth's crust meets other continental plates. In the past two months, tremors of 7.3, 6.5 and 6.0 have been recorded in the area, 1,000 kilometres north of New Zealand. Two years ago, a conservation worker was killed on Raoul Island when caught in a mudflow after a volcano erupted during an earthquake swarm.

Czech central bank raises interest rate to 3.25 percent The Czech National Bank raised its key interest rate to 3.25 percent Thursday, taking markets by surprise. The Czech Statistics Office earlier announced a 7.4 percent rise in average monthly wage levels in the second quarter of the year compared with the same period in 2006. Czech annual inflation rate fell slightly to 2.3 percent in July from 2.5 percent in June. Despite Thursday's increase to a five-year high, the cost of borrowing in the Czech Republic remained lower than in the 13-nation eurozone, where the key rate is currently 4.0 percent. Rates were last hiked by the national bank in July by a quarter percentage point following on from a similar hike in May. Another rise could still be on the cards by the end of the year, analysts "The need for higher rates was clearly marked out by today's news of faster wages rate growth," commented Raiffeisenbank analyst Michal Brozka. "Domestic factors were clearly predominant," underlined David Navratil of the Ceska Sporitelna bank. Elsewhere, financial markets are speculating that major central banks like the US Federal Reserve or the European Central Bank will either lower rates or leave them unchanged when policymakers meet next month.

And even with the stars, we have a tough fight ahead of us: There's the premiere of `24' and there's football on." These are strange days for traditional music awards shows. The recording industry is reeling, the concert-touring business is in retreat and television audiences have made it quite clear that their fascination lies with shows that create new celebrities, not the ones that honor existing stars. In 2006, "American Idol" hammered the first hour of the Grammy Awards in head-to-head ratings competition. The following year the producers of the grand old awards show responded by reluctantly adding an imitation "Idol" competition component to the broadcast. "Idol" also has sapped the AMAs of one of their defining traits, their proudly populist heritage; when the AMAs started in 1974, it was the show where music-buying fans chose the winners, not some rarefied academy. This year the stars are rushing to the AMAs and making the most of their stage time, especially with the all-important holiday sales season ramping up. Theater of the absurd: Minnesota bars thwart smoking ban by declaring everyone an actor All the world's a stage at some of Minnesota's bars. A new state ban on smoking in restaurants and other nightspots contains an exception for performers in theatrical productions. So some bars are getting around the ban by printing up playbills, encouraging customers to come in costume, and pronouncing them "actors." The customers are playing right along, merrily puffing away -- and sometimes speaking in funny accents and doing a little improvisation, too. The state Health Department is threatening to bring the curtain down on these sham productions. But for now, it's on with the show. At The Rock, a hard-rock and heavy-metal bar in suburban St. Paul, the "actors" during "theater night" do little more than sit around, drink, smoke and listen to the earsplitting music. "They're playing themselves before Oct. 1. You know, before there was a smoking ban," owner Brian Bauman explained. Shaping the words in the air with his hands, like a producer envisioning the marquee, he said: "We call the production, `Before the Ban!'" The smoking ban, passed by the Legislature last year, allows actors to light up in character during theatrical performances as long as patrons are notified in advance. About 30 bars in Minnesota have been exploiting the loophole by staging the faux theater productions and pronouncing cigarettes props, according to an anti-smoking group. "It's too bad they didn't put as much effort into protecting their employees from smoking," grumbled Jeanne Weigum, executive director of the Association for Nonsmokers. The Health Department this week vowed to begin cracking down on theater nights with fines of as much as $10,000 (euro6,528). "The law was enacted to protect Minnesotans from the serious health effects of secondhand smoke," Minnesota Health Commissioner Sanne Magnan said. "It is time for the curtain to fall on these theatrics." At The Rock earlier this week, a black stage curtain covered part of the entrance, and a sign next to it with an arrow read, "Stage Entrance." Along the opposite wall, below a sign saying "Props Dept.," was a stack of the only props needed: black ashtrays. At the door was a printed playbill for that night's program, with a list of names of the people portraying bartenders and security guards. Playing the owner: "Brian." Courtney Conk paid $1 for a button that said "Act Now" and pinned it to her shirt. That made her an actor for the night, entitling her to smoke. She turned in an understated, minimalist performance, sitting with cigarette in hand and talking to a bass player with the band. "I thought it was funny that they found a loophole," Conk said. "I'm more of an activist-actor tonight, you could say. I think it's kind of this way of saying what we think about the ban." While The Rock asks nothing of its actors by way of creativity, a few other bars have been a little more theatrical. At Barnacles Resort and Campground along Lake Mille Lacs, a "traveling tobacco troupe" dressed in medieval costume on the first theater night. Mark Benjamin, a lawyer who pushed bars to exploit the loophole, wore tights, a feathered cap and black "Hey, I'm a child of the '60s. I can do a little improv," he said. His improv amounted to speaking in medieval character to other patrons. In Hill City, Mike's Uptown owner Lisa Anderson has been offering theater night once a week. The bar had a Mardi Gras theme last Saturday, attracting about 30 patrons, most of them in costume. "I was dressed in a Victorian dress with the old fluffy thing that weighs 500 pounds," she said. "We had some fairies and some pirates and a group of girls -- I'm not sure what they were, but they had big boas and flashy makeup." Though there were no skits, Anderson said some people "start talking with different accents." She added: "It's turned into the funnest thing I can imagine." One bar on northern Minnesota's Iron Range, the Queen City Sports Place, calls its nightly smokefest "The Tobacco Monologues." Proving anew there's no business like show business, Anderson said her theater-night receipts have averaged $2,000 (euro1,305.57) -- up from $500 (euro326.39) right after the ban kicked in. Similarly, Bauman said revenue at The Rock dropped off 30 percent after the ban took effect, then shot back up to normal once the bar began allowing smoking again. He and other bar owners said they plan to continue putting on theater nights. "There's no question we were struggling," he said. "And we are extremely nervous that this is going to go away, and we will be back to the way it was."

Their name comes from Naxalbari, a village in West Bengal state where the movement was born in 1967. Maoist rebels fatally shot three villagers Friday in eastern India, a police official said. state near the Nepal border, said Anil Kumar Sinha, the area's At least 30 rebels took part in the attack in a village in Bihar deputy superintendent of police. Air China to begin daily nonstop flights between Beijing, Macao Air China, the country's flagship carrier, said it will begin daily, nonstop air service between Beijing and Macao from December 7. The new service, which will use a Boeing 737-800 aircraft, will be the first one between the two cities operated by a Chinese mainland airline company. Air Macao is currently the only carrier on the route.

Rugby League: Storm batter Raiders for big NRL win Premiership favourites Melbourne Storm overpowered the lowly Canberra Raiders 32-16 in Australia's National Rugby League on Saturday. The Raiders led for 38 minutes before the Storm hit top gear to clear away for their second win of the new season after losing to the Brisbane Broncos in last season's grand final. A storm lashed the ground 10 minutes before kick-off and rain bucketed down on the players during the warm-up and for periods during the match.
